<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="253" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1321,2029]" pageId="1" pageNumber="253">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,344,1393,1418]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="253" reason="1">Description.</emphasis>
Single specimen with R = 
<quantity box="[654,755,1393,1417]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.38" pageId="1" pageNumber="253" unit="mm" value="23.8">23.8 mm</quantity>
and r = 
<quantity box="[852,938,1393,1417]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.6" pageId="1" pageNumber="253" unit="mm" value="9.6">9.6 mm</quantity>
(R/r = 2.5). Abactinal surface covered with closely packed paxillae. Larger paxillae reaching more than 
<quantity box="[839,905,1429,1453]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="253" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
in diameter, with approximately 40 peripheral and 35 central spinelets.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1321,2029]" pageId="1" pageNumber="253">Number of superomarginal plates, 16; inferomarginal plates, 16. Superomarginal plates separated from inferomarginal plates by well-developed longitudinal fasciolar groove. Superomarginal plates covered with beadlike granules and a peripheral series of slender spinelets.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1321,2029]" pageId="1" pageNumber="253">All inferomarginal plates aligned opposite to superomarginal plates. Surface of inferomarginal plates completely covered with slender spinelets.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1321,2029]" pageId="1" pageNumber="253">
Actinal plate elliptical in shape, with slender spinelets. Single series of plates extending to 4th inferomarginal plate. Paired actinal plates located just behind mouth plates, followed by longitudinal series of 5 odd plates (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,917,940]" captionTargetBox="[158,1431,416,885]" captionTargetId="figure-397@2.[151,1436,411,893]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Patagiaster sphaerioplax Fisher, 1913 (RUMF-ZE-00032): A, abactinal view of entire animal in living condition; B, denuded actinal surface showing the 5 odd plates on the interradial midline. Scales: A = 10 mm; B = 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5252136" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5252136/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="253">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
); distal margin of outermost odd plate adjoining interradial suture between 1st inferomarginal plates.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1321,2029]" pageId="1" pageNumber="253">Each adambulacral plate with 7 relatively long, furrow spines, followed by 10–16 subambulacral spines arranged in more or less 3–4 longitudinal series.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1321,2029]" box="[199,735,1861,1885]" pageId="1" pageNumber="253">Madreporite completely concealed by spinelets.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="253" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1321,2029]" pageId="1" pageNumber="253">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1897,1922]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="253" reason="1">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species was known from the vicinity of 
<collectingRegion box="[872,976,1897,1921]" country="Philippines" name="Romblon" pageId="1" pageNumber="253">Romblon</collectingRegion>
Island of the 
<collectingCountry box="[1135,1337,1897,1921]" name="Philippines" pageId="1" pageNumber="253">Philippine Islands</collectingCountry>
at depth of 
<quantity box="[182,253,1933,1957]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.43" pageId="1" pageNumber="253" unit="m" value="143.0">143 m</quantity>
(
<typeStatus box="[269,319,1933,1957]" pageId="1" pageNumber="253">type</typeStatus>
locality), and the Flores Sea, 
<collectingCountry box="[657,766,1933,1957]" name="Indonesia" pageId="1" pageNumber="253">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
at depths of 
<quantity box="[914,1042,1933,1957]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.25" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="253" unit="m" value="425.0" valueMax="500.0" valueMin="350.0">350–500 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Jangoux, M. &amp; Ridder, C. D. &amp; Massin, C. &amp; Darsono, P." box="[1057,1284,1933,1957]" pageId="1" pageNumber="253" pagination="161 - 170" refId="ref5441" refString="Jangoux, M., Ridder, C. D., Massin, C. &amp; Darsono, P. (1989) The holothuroids, echinoids and asteroids (echinodermata) collected by the Snellius-II expedition. Netherlands Journal of Sea Research, 23 (2), 161 - 170." type="journal article" year="1989">
Jangoux 
<emphasis box="[1159,1209,1933,1957]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="253">et al</emphasis>
. 1989
</bibRefCitation>
). The present study represents the first record of the species from 
<collectingCountry box="[760,827,1970,1993]" name="Japan" pageId="1" pageNumber="253">Japan</collectingCountry>
. The distribution range of the species is extended to north.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="254" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,151,356]" pageId="2" pageNumber="254">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,152,176]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="254" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
The material collected mostly agrees with the original description of the species. We could not confirm whether the shape of 1–3 small spines on the inferomarginal plates of the examined specimen was lanceolate or not, probably because they were abraded and damaged during the dredging operations.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,151,356]" pageId="2" pageNumber="254">
The present study shows the colour in life of the abactinal surface as bright orange with the radial abactinal plates tinged with olive green (
<figureCitation box="[531,627,295,319]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,917,940]" captionTargetBox="[158,1431,416,885]" captionTargetId="figure-397@2.[151,1436,411,893]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Patagiaster sphaerioplax Fisher, 1913 (RUMF-ZE-00032): A, abactinal view of entire animal in living condition; B, denuded actinal surface showing the 5 odd plates on the interradial midline. Scales: A = 10 mm; B = 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5252136" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5252136/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="254">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
). Prior accounts have not reported the colour in life of this rarely encountered species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
